27/01/2011
SOFIA, Bulgaria -- The Sofia City Court on Wednesday (January 26th) sentenced Alexander Tomov, a former deputy prime minister, to nine years in prison for embezzlement. 
Tomov was found guilty of embezzling over 7m euros while he was CEO of Bulgaria's biggest steel mill, Kremikovtzi, between 2005 and 2008. 
He was also convicted of document fraud. 
Tomov served as deputy prime minister from 1990-1991 in a Socialist-led coalition government. 
He has denied all charges and has two weeks to appeal the verdict. 
(AP, bTV, BNT - 26/01/11)
